    "We denote the set of newly ranked triples (x, y +, y -) as D † λ(t+1).",
    "By applying the maximum likelihood objective of DPO [35,Equation (7)] to the pseudo preference dataset D † λ(t+1), we reduce the LLM policy optimization step of CAID tomaximize θ ∈ Θ E (x,y +,y -) ∼ D † λ(t+1) log σ β log π θ (y + | x) π ref (y + | x) -β log π θ (y -| x) π ref (y -| x).The pseudo preference-based DPO is also employed in [26,21], albeit with different dual updates that are found to be biased or unstable when evaluated in practice.",
    "We note that other DPO variants, such as SimPO [28], could also be used for the LLM policy optimization step in MoCAID, though this is beyond the scope of our work.",
    "Dual subgradient step with an online dataset of (x, y) ∼ D • π θ(t):λ(t + 1) = λ(t) -η E (x,y) ∼ D•π θ(t) [ h(x, y)] +.",
    "7:LLM policy optimization step with a pseudo preference dateset D † λ(t+1):θ(t + 1) ∈ argmax θ ∈ Θ E (x,y +,y -) ∼ D † λ(t+1) log σ β log π θ (y + | x) π ref (y + | x) -β log π θ (y -| x) π ref (y -| x).8: end for 9: Output: {θ ⋆ (t)} T t = 1.In the preference-based setting, we only have access to a human-annotated preference dataset D pref in format of (x, y 1, y 0, 1 r (y 1 ≻ y 0), {1 gi (y 1 ≻ y 0)} m i = 1), rather than reward and utility models (r, {g i } m i = 1)."
